assistant > To solve the expression \((6 \sim 1) \sim 6\), we need to follow the definition of the operation \(\sim\), which is defined as \(a \sim b = 1 \times a \times b\).

First, we calculate \(6 \sim 1\):

\[
6 \sim 1 = 1 \times 6 \times 1 = 6
\]

Next, we use the result to calculate \((6 \sim 1) \sim 6\):

\[
6 \sim 6 = 1 \times 6 \times 6 = 36
\]

Thus, the result of \((6 \sim 1) \sim 6\) is 36.
